2013 Special Jury Award]]<br/>Nomination\u2014[[Filmfare Award for Best Director]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Nishabd]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2007\n|\n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Blood Brothers (2007 Indian film)|Blood Brothers]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2007\n| {{ya}}\n|\n| {{ya}}\n| \n| Short film\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[No Smoking (2007 film)|No Smoking]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2007\n| \n| {{ya}}\n| \n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Dus Kahaniyaan]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2007\n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[U Me Aur Hum]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2008\n|\n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Haal-e-Dil]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2008\n|\n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Kaminey]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2009\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n|  Nominated\u2014Filmfare Award for Best Director<br/>Nominated\u2014[[Filmfare Award for Best Music Director]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Ishqiya]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2010\n|\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n|  National Film Award for Best Music Direction<br/>Nominated\u2014Filmfare Award for Best Director\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[7 Khoon Maaf]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2011\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Matru Ki Bijlee Ka Mandola]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2013\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Ek Thi Daayan]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2013\n|\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Dedh Ishqiya]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2014\n|\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Haider (film)|Haider]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2014\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| [[National Film Award for Best Screenplay]]<br/>National Film Award for Best Music Direction<br/>Nominated\u2014Filmfare Award for Best Director\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Drishyam (2015 film)|Drishyam]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2015\n|\n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Talvar (film)|Talvar]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2015\n|\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| [[National Film Award for Best Screenplay]]<br/>Nominated\u2014Filmfare Award for Best Film\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Hawaizaada]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2015\n|\n| \n| \n| {{ya}}\n| \n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Madaari]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2016\n|\n| \n| \n| {{ya}}\n| \n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Motu Patlu: King Of Kings]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2016\n|\n| \n| \n| {{ya}}\n| Animation film\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Rangoon (2017 Hindi film)|Rangoon]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2017\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| \n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|''[[Carbon (2018 film)|Carbon]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2018\n| \n| \n| \n| {{ya}}\n| Malayalam film<br/>[[Kerala State Film Award for Best Music Director]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|''[[Pataakha]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2018\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| \n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|''[[Sonchiriya]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2019\n| \n| \n| \n| {{ya}}\n| \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0080235|name=Vishal Bhardwaj}}\n* {{AllMovie name|id=vishal-bhardwaj-p221491|name=Vishal Bhardwaj}}\n\n{{NationalFilmAwardBestMusicDirection}}\n{{National Film Award Best Screenplay}}\n{{National Film Award Special Jury Award Feature Film}}\n{{KeralaStateFilmAwardBestMusicDirection}}\n{{Vishal Bhardwaj}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bhardwaj, Vishal}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Vishal Bhardwaj]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language film directors]]\n[[Category:Hindu College, Delhi alumni]]\n[[Category:Best Music Direction National Film Award winners]]\n[[Category:Indian male songwriters]]\n[[Category:Indian film score composers]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language lyricists]]\n[[Category:Indian male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Bollywood playback singers]]\n[[Category:Indian male film singers]]\n[[Category:People from Bijnor]]\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Hindi film score composers]]\n[[Category:Indian male singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian film directors]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Best Adapted Screenplay National Film Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Dialogue National Film Award winners]]\n[[Category:Special Jury Award (feature film) National Film Award winners]]\n[[Category:Directors who won the Best Children's Film National Film Award]]\n[[Category:Male film score composers]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the Indian television actor|Vishal Bhardwaj (actor)}}\n{{short description|Indian film director, screenwriter and composer}}\n{{good article}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = Vishal Bhardwaj\n| image           = Vishal Bhardwaj 2017.jpg\n| caption         = Bhardwaj in 2017\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1965|8|4}}\n| birth_place      = [[Bijnor]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], India\n| occupation      = Director, producer, writer, music director\n| years_active    = 1995\u2013present\n| spouse          = [[Rekha Bhardwaj]]\n}}\n'''Vishal Bhardwaj''' (born 4 August 1965)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.freepressjournal.in/entertainment/vishal-bhardwaj-birthday-special-his-films-views-and-upcoming-projects/1115522|title=Vishal Bhardwaj birthday special: His films, views and upcoming projects|last=Sonar|first=Mamta|work=The Free Press Journal|date=4 August 2017|accessdate=7 August 2018}}</ref> is an Indian film director, screenwriter, producer, music composer and playback singer. He is known for his work in Hindi cinema, and is the recipient of seven [[National Film Awards]] in four categories.\n\nBhardwaj made his debut as a music composer with the children's film ''[[Abhay (The Fearless)]]'' (1995), and received wider recognition with his compositions in [[Gulzar]]'s ''[[Maachis]]'' (1996). He received the [[Filmfare RD Burman Award for New Music Talent]] for the latter. He went on to compose music for the films ''[[Satya (1998 film)|Satya]]'' (1998) and ''[[Godmother (film)|Godmother]]'' (1999). For the latter, he garnered the [[National Film Award for Best Music Direction]]. Bhardwaj made his directorial debut with the children's film ''[[Makdee]]'' (2002), for which he also composed the music. He garnered critical acclaim and several accolades for writing and directing the Indian adaptations of three tragedies by [[William Shakespeare]]: ''[[Maqbool]]'' (2003) from ''[[Macbeth]]'', ''[[Omkara (2006 film)|Omkara]]'' (2006) from ''[[Othello]]'', and ''[[Haider (film)|Haider]]'' (2014) from ''[[Hamlet]]''. He has also directed the caper thriller ''[[Kaminey]]'', the black comedy ''[[7 Khoon Maaf]]'' (2011), and the satire ''[[Matru Ki Bijlee Ka Mandola]]'' (2013).\n\nIn addition, Bhardwaj produces films under his banner VB Pictures. He has co-written and produced the films ''[[Ishqiya]]'' (2010), its sequel ''[[Dedh Ishqiya]]'' (2014), and the crime drama ''[[Talvar (film)|Talvar]]'' (2015), among others. He has composed the musical score for each of his directorial and production ventures, and frequently collaborates with the lyricist Gulzar. He is married to playback singer [[Rekha Bhardwaj]].\n\n==Personal life==\nBhardwaj was born on 4 August 1965, in [[Chandpur]] city in District [[Bijnor]], [[Uttar Pradesh]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/birthday-special-vishal-bhardwajs-best-film-vote/20150804.htm|title=Birthday Special: Vishal Bhardwaj's BEST film? VOTE!|publisher=Rediff.com|date=4 August 2015|accessdate=7 August 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"koimoi\">{{cite web|url=http://www.koimoi.com/director/vishal-bhardwaj/|title=Vishal Bhardwaj's Biography|publisher=[[Koimoi]]|accessdate=8 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160130075555/http://www.koimoi.com/director/vishal-bhardwaj/|archivedate=30 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> His mother Satya Bhardwaj, was a homemaker, and father Ram Bhardwaj, was a sugarcane inspector.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/I-wish-I-could-make-more-female-oriented-films-Vishal-Bhardwaj/articleshow/17571001.cms|title=I wish I could make more female-oriented films: Vishal Bhardwaj|last=Gupta|first=Priya|work=The Times of India|date=12 December 2012|accessdate=3 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813220711/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/I-wish-I-could-make-more-female-oriented-films-Vishal-Bhardwaj/articleshow/17571001.cms|archivedate=13 August 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> His father also wrote poetry and lyrics for Hindi films.<ref name=\"koimoi\"/> He and his family lived in [[Najibabad]] until he completed class five in school.<ref name=\"mint\">{{cite news|url=http://www.livemint.com/Leisure/yi8lU2eamGLdnSakVfG5ZP/Vishal8217s-world.html|title=Vishal's world|last=Misra|first=Neelesh|authorlink=Neelesh Misra|work=[[Mint (newspaper)|Mint]]|date=19 February 2011|accessdate=8 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119232748/http://www.livemint.com/Leisure/yi8lU2eamGLdnSakVfG5ZP/Vishal8217s-world.html|archivedate=19 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> They later moved to [[Meerut]], where he used to play [[cricket]] for the states under-19 team.<ref name=\"mint\"/> He could not pursue cricket because the day before a tournament, his thumb broke during a practise session.<ref name=\"vb\">{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/i-am-my-own-audience-vishal-bhardwaj/story-CbIQhAmX9yuREg8OqA75BO.html|title=I am my own audience: Vishal Bhardwaj|last=Singh|first=Prashant|work=Hindustan Times|date=25 December 2015|accessdate=16 January 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106101144/http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/i-am-my-own-audience-vishal-bhardwaj/story-CbIQhAmX9yuREg8OqA75BO.html|archivedate=6 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He had an elder brother, who struggled for years in Mumbai to become a film producer and later died of a heart attack.<ref name=\"mint\"/> He composed a song at the age of seventeen. After hearing it, his father discussed it with music director [[Usha Khanna]]. She used it for the film ''Yaar Kasam'' (1985).<ref name=\"mint\"/> Bhardwaj later moved to Delhi to pursue his graduation at the [[Hindu College, University of Delhi]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archive.mid-day.com/entertainment/2007/nov/332637.htm|title=Vishal Bhardwaj and Imtiaz Ali get nostalgic about their college days|work=[[Mid Day]]|date=5 November 2007}}</ref> He met his wife and playback singer [[Rekha Bhardwaj]]  during the college annual function; she was a year senior to him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://specials.rediff.com/movies/2009/apr/13sd2-rekha-bhardwaj-on-music-and-more.htm|title=When I came to Mumbai, I was not looking at doing films|publisher=[[Rediff.com]]|accessdate=10 July 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130507015705/http://specials.rediff.com/movies/2009/apr/13sd2-rekha-bhardwaj-on-music-and-more.htm|archivedate=7 May 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He is also an avid [[tennis]] player.<ref name=\"open\">{{cite news|url=http://www.openthemagazine.com/article/art-culture/inside-the-mind-of-vishal-bhardwaj|title=Inside the Mind of Vishal Bhardwaj|last=Chaubey|first=Abhishek|authorlink=Abhishek Chaubey|work=[[Open (Indian magazine)|OPEN]]|date=26 February 2011|accessdate=10 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120015136/http://www.openthemagazine.com/article/art-culture/inside-the-mind-of-vishal-bhardwaj|archivedate=20 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nBhardwaj started playing [[Pump organ|harmonium]] for friends who were [[ghazal]] singers. After a few years, he took up a job with a music company called CBS in Delhi.<ref name=\"mint\"/><ref name=\"outlook\">{{cite news|title=Krzysztof... In Meerut|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article/krzysztof-in-meerut/261415|last=Joshi|first=Namrata|work=[[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]]|date=31 August 2009|accessdate=17 June 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007015538/http://www.outlookindia.com/article/Krzysztof-In-Meerut/261415|archivedate=7 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He later went to Mumbai to become a music composer, and he only took to directing films to create the opportunity to compose music.<ref name=\"open\"/>\nHis interest in film direction kindled after watching [[Quentin Tarantino]]'s ''[[Pulp Fiction]]'' (1994), and [[Krzysztof Kie\u015blowski]]'s television series ''[[Dekalog]]'', during a film festival in [[Thiruvananthapuram]].<ref name=\"mint\"/><ref name=\"outlook\"/>\n\n===Music composer===\nIn 1995, Bhardwaj made his debut as a music composer for the children's film ''[[Abhay (The Fearless)]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cfsindia.org/abhay-the-fearless/|title=Abhay (The fearless)|publisher=[[Children's Film Society, India]]|accessdate=5 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316034816/http://cfsindia.org/abhay-the-fearless/|archivedate=16 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He then went on to compose music for ''[[Fauji (1995 film)|Fauji]]'' (1995), and ''[[Sanshodhan]]'' (1996).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saavn.com/s/album/hindi/Fauji-1995/yIKecD8WGIg_|title=Fauji|publisher=[[Saavn]]|accessdate=5 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160309201417/http://www.saavn.com/s/album/hindi/Fauji-1995/yIKecD8WGIg_|archivedate=9 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Sanshodhan-Year-1996-Govind-Nihalani/dp/B007ZZMMZO|title=Sanshodhan (Year 1996) a Film By Govind Nihalani - Cinemas of India|accessdate=5 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150706164008/http://www.amazon.com/Sanshodhan-Year-1996-Govind-Nihalani/dp/B007ZZMMZO|archivedate=6 July 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\nIn 1996, he served as the music director for [[Gulzar]]'s ''[[Maachis]]'' (1996), for which he received the [[Filmfare RD Burman Award for New Music Talent]].<ref name=\"makdee\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/entertai/2002/nov/06vishal.htm|title=I want to scare kids|last=Jha|first=Subhash K.|authorlink=Subhash K. Jha|date=6 November 2002|publisher=Rediff.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103211539/http://www.rediff.com/entertai/2002/nov/06vishal.htm|archivedate=3 November 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The film depicted the transformation of boys into terrorists during the [[Punjab insurgency]] in [[Punjab, India|Punjab]] in the 1980s.<ref name=\"peer\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/opinion/op-ed/i-have-tried-to-add-a-reporters-sense-of-realism-to-haider-basharat-peer/article6466504.ece|title=I have tried to add a reporter's sense of realism to Haider: Basharat Peer|last=Vincent|first=Pheroze L.|work=The Hindu|date=2 October 2014|accessdate=3 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141002205032/http://www.thehindu.com/opinion/op-ed/i-have-tried-to-add-a-reporters-sense-of-realism-to-haider-basharat-peer/article6466504.ece|archivedate=2 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The soundtrack composed by Bhardwaj became an anthem for the politically restive college youth at that time.<ref name=\"peer\"/> He later collaborated with him on TV serials such as ''[[Fushigi no Kuni no Alice|Alice in Wonderland]]'' and ''Gubbare''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zeetv.com/shows/gubbare/|title=Gubbare : About The Show|publisher=[[Zee TV]]|accessdate=5 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151014083733/http://www.zeetv.com/shows/gubbare/|archivedate=14 October 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> His further projects included ''[[Betaabi]]'' (1997), ''[[Tunnu Ki Tina]]'' (1997), ''[[Satya (1998 film)|Satya]]'' (1998) and ''[[Hu Tu Tu]]'' (1999).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-vishal-bhardwajs-melodious-ten/20110120.htm#1|title=Vishal Bhardwaj's melodious ten!|publisher=Rediff.com|date=19 January 2011|accessdate=5 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151108141741/http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-vishal-bhardwajs-melodious-ten/20110120.htm#1|archivedate=8 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/154747/Tunnu-Ki-Tina/details|title=Tinnu Ki Tina (1997)|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=5 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120003727/http://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/154747/Tunnu-Ki-Tina/details|archivedate=20 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> At the [[46th National Film Awards]], Bhardwaj received the [[National Film Award for Best Music Direction]] for his critically acclaimed score in ''[[Godmother (film)|Godmother]]'' (1999).<ref name=\"god\">{{cite web|url=http://dff.nic.in/2011/46_nff_1999.pdf|title=46th National Film Awards|publisher=[[Directorate of Film Festivals]]|accessdate=12 March 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310180429/http://dff.nic.in/2011/46_nff_1999.pdf|archivedate=10 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2010, he composed the music for his production venture ''[[Ishqiya]]'', which garnered him his second National Film Award for Best Music Direction.<ref name=\"nfa\">{{cite web|title=58th National Film Awards|url=http://dff.nic.in/Press%20Release%20-%2058th%20National%20Film%20Awards%20Winners%202010.pdf|publisher=Directorate of Film Festivals|accessdate=29 March 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708120534/http://dff.nic.in/Press%20Release%20-%2058th%20National%20Film%20Awards%20Winners%202010.pdf|archivedate=8 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He also composed music for ''[[Jungle Book Sh\u014dnen Mowgli]]'', the Hindi dubbed version of the [[anime]] adaptation of [[Rudyard Kipling]]'s original collection of stories, ''[[The Jungle Book]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-in-school/a-romp-through-the-jungle-book/article4236715.ece|title=A romp through The Jungle Book|work=[[The Hindu]]|date=25 December 2012|accessdate=21 October 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906005302/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-in-school/a-romp-through-the-jungle-book/article4236715.ece|archivedate=6 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Apart from feature films, Bhardwaj has provided music for music albums such as ''Sunset Point'' (2000), ''Ishqa Ishqa'' (2002) and ''Barse Barse'' (2011).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/barse-barse-ep/id451504793|title=Barse Barse|publisher=[[iTunes]]|accessdate=5 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120021227/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/barse-barse-ep/id451504793|archivedate=20 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/in-sunset-point-gulzar-is-the-fulcrum-of-the-team/1/244930.html|title=Poetic rendezvous|last=Ranjit|first=S. Sahaya|work=[[India Today]]|date=9 October 2000|accessdate=5 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120002933/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/in-sunset-point-gulzar-is-the-fulcrum-of-the-team/1/244930.html|archivedate=20 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/gulzars-ishqa-ishqa-mw0001896434|title=Gulzar's Ishqa-Ishqa|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=5 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120120212/http://www.allmusic.com/album/gulzars-ishqa-ishqa-mw0001896434|archivedate=20 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He frequently collaborates with Gulzar.<ref name=\"koimoi\"/>\n\n===Writer and director===\nBhardwaj made his directorial debut with the horror film ''[[Makdee]]'' (2002), starring [[Shabana Azmi]], [[Makarand Deshpande]] and [[Shweta Prasad]]. The film tells the story of twin young girls and an alleged witch in a mansion.<ref name=\"makdee\"/> It was screened in the Critics' Week (Spotlight on India) section at the [[2003 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Vishal-Bharadwajs-Makdee-to-be-aired-at-Cannes/articleshow/21684090.cms|title=Vishal Bharadwaj's ''Makdee'' to be aired at Cannes|work=[[The Times of India]]|date=9 September 2002|accessdate=3 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nBhardwaj had read a short version of [[William Shakespeare]]'s ''[[Macbeth]]'' and wanted to turn it into a gangster film.<ref name=\"vb\"/> He had seen [[Akira Kurosawa]]'s ''[[Throne of Blood]]'' (1957), which was also inspired by Macbeth. It inspired Bhardwaj to make it into a feature film.<ref name=\"pais\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2003/nov/06vishal.htm|title=Maqbool is not meant for Shakespearean scholars|last=Pais|first=Arthur J|publisher=Rediff.com|date=6 November 2003|accessdate=3 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160803155714/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2003/nov/06vishal.htm|archivedate=3 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He then started working with [[Abbas Tyrewala]] to adapt the play.<ref name=\"pais\"/> Bhardwaj then came up with its film adaptation ''[[Maqbool]]'' (2003), starring [[Pankaj Kapur]], [[Irrfan Khan]] and [[Tabu (actress)|Tabu]]; it was set against the backdrop of Mumbai underworld. The film was screened at the [[2004 Cannes Film Festival]] and at the [[2003 Toronto International Film Festival|2003 Toronto Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/bollywood-star-aishwarya-rai-sizzles-at-57th-edition-of-cannes-film-festival/1/196007.html|title=Riviera rhapsody|last1=Bhasi|first1=Ishara|last2=Rohatgi|first2=Shilpa|work=India Today|date=24 May 2004|accessdate=2 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150722095357/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/bollywood-star-aishwarya-rai-sizzles-at-57th-edition-of-cannes-film-festival/1/196007.html|archivedate=22 July 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=JdNCBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA79&lpg=PA79&dq=maqbool+at+toronto#v=onepage&q=maqbool%20at%20toronto&f=false|title=Bollywood Shakespeares|last1=Dionne|first1=Craig|last2=Kapadia|first2=Parmita|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|year=2014|isbn=9781137375568|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180203082159/https://books.google.com/books?id=JdNCBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA79&lpg=PA79&dq=maqbool+at+toronto&source=bl&ots=mUNwS07kV_&sig=UF0E4BX1VUpWtgeYZvnLyRZkRA8&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi5r5a5xrrJAhVQWI4KHVjNAJMQ6AEIRTAG#v=onepage&q=maqbool%20at%20toronto&f=false|archivedate=3 February 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Sita Menon of [[Rediff.com]] in her review called it \"..a visual gallery that is an intelligent blend of dark, tragic overtones and comic, satirical undertones.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2004/jan/30maqbool.htm|title=Watch Maqbool. It is class!|last=Menon|first=Sita|publisher=Rediff.com|date=30 January 2004|accessdate=2 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150822122115/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2004/jan/30maqbool.htm|archivedate=22 August 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[CNN-IBN]] listed ''Maqbool'' as \"one of the 100 greatest Indian films of all time\" in a 2013 list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/photogallery/13200-17.html |title=100 Years of Indian Cinema: The 100 greatest Indian films of all time |publisher=[[CNN-IBN]] |date=17 April 2013 |accessdate=12 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130425234438/http://ibnlive.in.com/photogallery/13200-17.html |archivedate=25 April 2013 |url-status=unfit }}</ref> In 2010, Film critic [[Raja Sen]] mentioned it in \"The Top 75 Hindi Films of the Decade\" list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-the-top-75-hindi-films-of-the-decade/20100209.htm|title=The Top 75 Hindi Films of the Decade|last=Sen|first=Raja|authorlink=Raja Sen|publisher=Rediff.com|date=9 February 2010|accessdate=2 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105115534/http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-the-top-75-hindi-films-of-the-decade/20100209.htm|archivedate=5 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Bhardwaj again adapted Shakespeare's tragedy ''[[Othello]]'', as ''[[Omkara (2006 film)|Omkara]]''. Set against the backdrop of the political system in Uttar Pradesh, the film had [[Ajay Devgan]] as the titular character.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/shropshire/films/bollywood/2006/05/omkara_preview.shtml|title=Omkara|accessdate=19 May 2009|last=Gajjar|first=Manish|date=May 2006|publisher=BBC|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111111074642/http://www.bbc.co.uk/shropshire/films/bollywood/2006/05/omkara_preview.shtml|archivedate=11 November 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It premiered at the 6th [[Marrakech International Film Festival]], and was screened at the [[Cairo International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1061206/asp/nation/story_7101465.asp|title=Omkara puzzle here, prize there|accessdate=8 July 2010|last=Roy|first=Amit|date=6 December 2006|work=[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024102206/http://www.telegraphindia.com/1061206/asp/nation/story_7101465.asp|archivedate=24 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> At the [[54th National Film Awards]], Bhardwaj received the [[National Film Award \u2013 Special Jury Award (Feature Film)|Special Jury Award]] for the film.<ref name=\"omkara\">{{cite web|url=http://dff.nic.in/2011/54th_nff_2006.pdf|title=54th National Film Awards|publisher=Directorate of Film Festivals|accessdate=24 March 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029193647/http://dff.nic.in/2011/54th_nff_2006.pdf|archivedate=29 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''Omkara'' met with critical acclaim, but was a [[box office bomb|box office disappointment]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2006/aug/01box.htm|title=Critics hot, box office cold over Omkara|publisher=Rediff.com|date=1 August 2006|accessdate=2 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150829063801/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2006/aug/01box.htm|archivedate=29 August 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It however opened to positive box-office response in North America and the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2006/aug/02ajp.htm|title=Foreign audiences flock to Omkara|last=Pais|first=Arthur J|publisher=Rediff.com|date=2 August 2006|accessdate=2 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150829061343/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2006/aug/02ajp.htm|archivedate=29 August 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nBhardwaj's next project was the children's film, ''[[The Blue Umbrella (2005 film)|The Blue Umbrella]]'' (2005), based on [[Ruskin Bond]]'s [[The Blue Umbrella|novel of the same name]]. It won the [[National Film Award for Best Children's Film]] in 2005.<ref name=\"umbrella\">{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/movie-reviews/The-Blue-Umbrella/movie-review/2273345.cms|title=The Blue Umbrella Movie Review|work=The Times of India|date=11 August 2007|accessdate=2 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180203082159/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/movie-reviews/The-Blue-Umbrella/movie-review/2273345.cms|archivedate=3 February 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> His followup was ''[[Blood Brothers (2007 Indian film)|Blood Brothers]]'' (2007), a short-film on [[HIV/AIDS]], with a run time of 13 minutes. It tells the story of a young man who, after finding out that he is [[HIV-positive people|HIV positive]], allows his life to fall apart.<ref>{{cite news|title=Democratisation of cinema brings best films to India|url=http://www.sunday-guardian.com/masala-art/democratisation-of-cinema-brings-best-films-to-india|accessdate=8 May 2012|work=[[The Sunday Guardian]]|date=14 March 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208121800/http://www.sunday-guardian.com/masala-art/democratisation-of-cinema-brings-best-films-to-india|archivedate=8 December 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It was a part of the 'AIDS JaaGo', a series of four short films, directed by [[Mira Nair]], [[Santosh Sivan]], and [[Farhan Akhtar]] in a joint initiative by Nair and the [[Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Mira Nair, Farhan Akhtar to make films on AIDS|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2007/jan/22mira.htm|publisher=Rediff.com|date=22 January 2007|accessdate=30 March 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070305171037/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2007/jan/22mira.htm|archivedate=5 March 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The series premiered at the [[2007 Toronto International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2007-11-07/news/27685691_1_indian-films-mirabai-films-indian-cinema|title=Indian films to be special attraction in Dubai festival|work=[[The Economic Times]]|date=7 November 2007|accessdate=2 November 2015}}</ref> The same year, he also served as a writer for [[Sanjay Gupta (director)|Sanjay Gupta]]'s [[anthology film]], ''[[Dus Kahaniyaan]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/moviemicro/cast/id/201730|title=Dus Kahaniyaan (2007)|publisher=[[Bollywood Hungama]]|accessdate=4 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117114654/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/moviemicro/cast/id/201730|archivedate=17 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Bhardwaj came up with the [[Caper story|Caper]] thriller ''[[Kaminey]]'', starring [[Shahid Kapoor]] and [[Priyanka Chopra]]. The film follows the rivalry between identical twins, one with a [[lisp]] and one with a [[stammer]]. The story was bought by him from a Kenyan writer.<ref>{{cite news|title=Scripting Kaminey|url=http://www.mumbaimirror.com/columns/columnists/aseem-chhabra/Scripting-Kaminey/articleshow/15947355.cms|last=Chhabra|first=Aseem|work=[[Mumbai Mirror]]|date=16 August 2009|accessdate=17 August 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117064658/http://www.mumbaimirror.com/columns/columnists/aseem-chhabra/Scripting-Kaminey/articleshow/15947355.cms|archivedate=17 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Saif too old, Shahid right for Kaminey|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/news-interviews/Saif-too-old-Shahid-right-for-Kaminey/articleshow/4805758.cms?referral=PM|last=Mirani|first=Indu|work=The Times of India|date=22 July 2009|accessdate=4 June 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140818111209/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/news-interviews/Saif-too-old-Shahid-right-for-Kaminey/articleshow/4805758.cms?referral=PM|archivedate=18 August 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It opened to generally positive reviews. [[Anupama Chopra]] gave a rating of 4 out of 5 and wrote \"Kaminey is the best Bollywood film I've seen this year. It's an audacious, original rollercoaster ride. Written and directed by Vishal Bhardwaj, Kaminey requires patience and attention but the pay off is more than worth it.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Kaminey Review|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/movie-reviews/kaminey-416|last=Chopra|first=Anupama|authorlink=Anupama Chopra|publisher=[[NDTV]]|date=14 August 2009|accessdate=20 November 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141120072326/http://movies.ndtv.com/movie-reviews/kaminey-416|archivedate=20 November 2014}}</ref> ''Kaminey'' was also a financial success earning over {{INRConvert|700|m}} worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=312&catName=TGlmZXRpbWU= |title=Top Lifetime Grossers Worldwide|archivedate=21 October 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021202725/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=312&catName=TGlmZXRpbWU=|publisher=[[Box Office India]]|accessdate=28 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Vishal Bhardwaj.jpg|thumb|right|Bhardwaj in 2012]]\n''[[7 Khoon Maaf]]'' (2011), a film based on the Ruskin Bond's short story, ''Susanna's Seven Husbands'', was Bhardwaj's next directorial venture. The story revolves around Susanna Anna-Marie Johannes (played by Priyanka Chopra) who murders her seven husbands in an unending quest for love. The film was written collaboratively by Bhardwaj, Bond and American writer [[Matthew Robbins (screenwriter)|Matthew Robbins]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ruskin Bond on 7 Khoon Maaf|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1110217/jsp/entertainment/story_13592167.jsp|last=Chakraborty Lahiri|first=Samhita|work=The Telegraph|date=17 February 2011|accessdate=4 May 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110831142022/http://www.telegraphindia.com/1110217/jsp/entertainment/story_13592167.jsp|archivedate=31 August 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It released on 18 February 2011 and met with mixed to positive reviews.<ref>{{cite news|title=Priyanka outdoes herself in Saat Khoon Maaf|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/news-interviews/Priyanka-outdoes-herself-in-Saat-Khoon-Maaf/articleshow/6787388.cms|work=The Times of India|accessdate=21 November 2011|first=Smrity|last=Sharma|date=22 October 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101024215540/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/news-interviews/Priyanka-outdoes-herself-in-Saat-Khoon-Maaf/articleshow/6787388.cms|archivedate=24 October 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Zee News]] in its four out of five star review mentioned: \"Vishal Bhardwaj does it again. The maverick filmmaker has once again woven magic with his latest blockbuster Saat Khoon Maaf\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Review: '7 Khoon Maaf' is dark, engaging and unapologetic|url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/bollywood/review-7-khoon-maaf-is-dark-engaging-and-unapologetic_82077.html|publisher=[[Zee News]]|date=19 February 2011|accessdate=22 April 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202150829/http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/bollywood/review-7-khoon-maaf-is-dark-engaging-and-unapologetic_82077.html|archivedate=2 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Bhardwaj directed ''[[Matru Ki Bijlee Ka Mandola]]'', a [[political satire]] set in the rustic surroundings of a village in [[Haryana]]. It starred [[Anushka Sharma]] and [[Imran Khan (Bollywood actor)|Imran Khan]] in the lead roles, with Pankaj Kapur and Shabana Azmi in supporting ones.<ref>{{cite web|title=Movie Review&nbsp;\u2014 Matru Ki Bijlee Ka Mandola: Done in by half measures|url=http://in.reuters.com/article/2013/01/14/matru-ki-bijlee-ka-mandola-idINDEE90A03Q20130114|last=Jamkhandikar|first=Shilpa|work=[[Reuters]]|date=14 January 2013|accessdate=15 January 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130115221902/http://in.reuters.com/article/2013/01/14/matru-ki-bijlee-ka-mandola-idINDEE90A03Q20130114|archivedate=15 January 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Bhardwaj also choreographed a song \"Oye boy Charlie\" in the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/vishal-bhardwaj-takes-over-oye-boy-choreography-630767|title=Vishal Bhardwaj takes over Oye Boy choreography|publisher=NDTV|date=30 December 2012|accessdate=3 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160603091322/http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/vishal-bhardwaj-takes-over-oye-boy-choreography-630767|archivedate=3 June 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\nThe film received mixed reviews from critics,<ref>{{cite web|title=Matru Ki Bijlee Ka Mandola (2013)|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/matru_ki_bijlee_ka_mandola/|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=10 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151007153308/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/matru_ki_bijlee_ka_mandola|archivedate=7 October 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and underperformed at the box office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=5293&nCat=|title=Matru Ki Bijlee Ka Mandola Is A Huge Flop|publisher=Box Office India|accessdate=15 January 2013|date=14 January 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130115031214/http://boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=5293&nCat=|archivedate=15 January 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/boxdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=5308&nCat=|title=Inkaar Poor Opening Matru Ki Bijlee Ka Mandola Poor First Week|publisher=Box Office India|accessdate=24 January 2013|date=19 January 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130122021238/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/boxdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=5308&nCat=|archivedate=22 January 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Bhardwaj made his stage debut with the [[opera]] 'A Flowering Tree\u2019. It was based on a classic folk tale by Kannada writer and scholar [[A. K. Ramanujan]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Vishal Bhardwaj: Directing opera opened new window in my mind|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/vishal-bhardwaj-directing-opera-opened-new-window-in-my-mind/|work=[[The Indian Express]]|date=8 May 2014|accessdate=5 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151026042545/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/vishal-bhardwaj-directing-opera-opened-new-window-in-my-mind/|archivedate=26 October 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He completed his William Shakespeare's trilogy with ''[[Haider (film)|Haider]]'' (2014), based on the tragedy ''[[Hamlet]]''. Set during the [[Kashmir conflict|Kashmir conflict of 1995]], the film starred Shahid Kapoor in the titular role, for which he along with Bhardwaj charged no money.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bhattacharya|first=Roshmila|title=Shahid Kapoor and Vishal Bhardwaj charged no money for Haider|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Shahid-Kapoor-and-Vishal-Bhardwaj-charged-no-money-for-Haider/articleshow/37993571.cms|accessdate=4 July 2015|work=The Times of India|date=8 July 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150227122547/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Shahid-Kapoor-and-Vishal-Bhardwaj-charged-no-money-for-Haider/articleshow/37993571.cms|archivedate=27 February 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''Haider'' garnered critical acclaim, though was controversial among Hindu nationalists for its portrayal of the conflict in Kashmir.<ref>{{cite news|last=Vats|first=Vaibhav|title=Kashmiri 'Hamlet' Stirs Rage in India|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/28/movies/haider-angers-hindu-nationalists-but-excites-film-critics.html|accessdate=17 July 2015|work=The New York Times|date=27 October 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414210124/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/28/movies/haider-angers-hindu-nationalists-but-excites-film-critics.html|archivedate=14 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-29502393 |last=Pandey|first=Vikas|title=Haider: Why is 'Indian Hamlet' controversial?|publisher=BBC|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141027152144/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-29502393|archivedate=27 October 2014|date=7 October 2014 |accessdate=7 October 2014 }}</ref> [[CNN-IBN]]'s [[Rajeev Masand]] called it \"an elegant, thrilling film that casts a brave, unflinching eye on the Kashmir struggle.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Masand|first=Rajeev|authorlink=Rajeev Masand|title=Bard target|url=http://www.rajeevmasand.com/reviews/our-films/bard-target-2/|publisher=RajeevMasand.com|date=2 October 2014|accessdate=2 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924231313/http://www.rajeevmasand.com/reviews/our-films/bard-target-2/|archivedate=24 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> At the [[62nd National Film Awards]], Bhardwaj won the [[National Film Award for Best Music Direction|Best Music Director]] and [[National Film Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay (Dialogues)]] award.<ref name=\"dialogue\">{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/62nd-national-film-awards-winners-haider-wins-five-queen-two/|title=62nd National Film Awards' winners: 'Haider' wins five, Kangana Ranaut's 'Queen' two|work=The Indian Express|date=24 March 2015|accessdate=24 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150325062007/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/62nd-national-film-awards-winners-haider-wins-five-queen-two/|archivedate=25 March 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=62nd National Film Awards for 2014 (Press Release)|url=http://dff.nic.in/writereaddata/62nd%20National%20Film%20Awards%202014%20-%20Press%20Release.pdf|publisher=Directorate of Film Festivals|date=24 February 2015|accessdate=25 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402123148/http://dff.nic.in/writereaddata/62nd%20National%20Film%20Awards%202014%20-%20Press%20Release.pdf|archivedate=2 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It also received nominations for [[Filmfare Award for Best Film|Best Film]] and [[Filmfare Award for Best Director|Best Director]] at the [[60th Filmfare Awards]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Nominations for the 60th Britannia Filmfare Awards|url=http://www.filmfare.com/news/nominations-for-the-60th-britannia-filmfare-awards-8237.html|work=[[Filmfare]]|date=19 January 2015|accessdate=15 April 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160110120443/http://www.filmfare.com/news/nominations-for-the-60th-britannia-filmfare-awards-8237.html|archivedate=10 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAfter two-year hiatus, Bhardwaj returned to direct ''[[Rangoon (2016 film)|Rangoon]]'', a romantic drama set during [[World War II]], starring [[Kangana Ranaut]], Saif Ali Khan and Shahid Kapoor. About the film, Bhardwaj said: \"In history very few people know that India was also involved in the war. On the Burma border the British Indian army was fighting against Subhash Chandra Bose\u2019s INA (Indian National Army), who were then with Japanese army and Indians were killing Indians at the Burma border.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/rangoon-not-inspired-by-casablanca-vishal-bhardwaj/|title='Rangoon' not inspired by 'Casablanca': Vishal Bhardwaj|work=The Indian Express|date=10 October 2015|accessdate=17 March 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170112023132/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/rangoon-not-inspired-by-casablanca-vishal-bhardwaj/|archivedate=12 January 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The film opened to generally mixed reviews and failed to find a wide audience at the box office.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rangoon box office collection: Kangana Ranaut, Shahid Kapoor film is a flop|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/rangoon-box-office-collection-kangana-ranaut-shahid-kapoor-film-4552864/|accessdate=6 March 2017|work=The Indian Express|date=3 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Bhardwaj wrote, co-produced and directed ''[[Pataakha]]'' starring [[Sanya Malhotra]] and debutant [[Radhika Madan]] as two quarrelsome sisters. It was based on the short story ''Do Behenein'' by Rajasthani writer and teacher Charan Singh Pathik, which he had read in 2013 in [[Sahitya Kala Parishad]] journal and had \"loved\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/vishal-bhardwajs-pataakha-is-the-story-of-real-life-sisters/articleshow/65859257.cms|title=Vishal Bhardwaj's 'Pataakha' is the story of real-life sisters|work=The Times of India|date=19 September 2018|accessdate=4 October 2018}}</ref> Udita Jhunjhunwala of ''[[Mint (newspaper)|Mint]]'' called the film \"real and gritty\" with Bhardwaj creating an \"altogether authentic world\". She however, felt that the film was stretched in length and \"squanders its material advantage to pad out a fable that splutters and grunts before it gains momentum.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.livemint.com/Consumer/uQ7cQkCDhUoxqmaYS8rLBK/Movie-Review-Pataakha-has-the-fuse-but-not-the-firepower.html|title=Movie Review: 'Pataakha' has the fuse, but not the firepower|last=Jhunjhunwala|first=Udita|work=Mint|date=28 October 2018|accessdate=4 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs of February 2018, Bhardwaj will direct [[Deepika Padukone]] and Irrfan Khan in the crime drama ''Rani'', about a gangster in the 1980s who attempts to assassinate [[Dawood Ibrahim]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/deepika-padukone-irrfan-khan-vishal-bharadwaj-film-is-titled-rani-5066734/|title=Exclusive: Deepika Padukone, Vishal Bharadwaj film is titled Rani|date=16 February 2018|work=The Indian Express|access-date=16 February 2018}}</ref> He will serve as the show-runner of the series adapted from [[Salman Rushdie]]'s novel ''[[Midnight's Children]]'' for [[Netflix]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.news18.com/news/movies/vishal-bhardwaj-to-direct-salman-rushdies-novel-midnights-children-for-netflix-1954569.html|title=Vishal Bhardwaj to Direct Salman Rushdie's Novel Midnight's Children for Netflix|publisher=CNN-News18|date=29 November 2018|accessdate=3 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Producer===\nBhardwaj has been producing his own films under his banner VB Pictures. In 2010, he produced the [[black comedy]] ''[[Ishqiya]]''. Starring [[Vidya Balan]], [[Naseeruddin Shah]] and [[Arshad Warsi]]; the film was directed by debutant [[Abhishek Chaubey]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1100130/jsp/entertainment/story_12045388.jsp|title=Passion play|last=Gupta|first=Pratim D.|authorlink=Pratim D. Gupta|date=30 January 2010|accessdate=19 March 2010|work=The Telegraph|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100305093914/http://www.telegraphindia.com/1100130/jsp/entertainment/story_12045388.jsp|archivedate=5 March 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Chaubey had earlier assisted and co-wrote several of Bhardwaj's film. The film was an average grosser at the box-office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/Years/years_detail/2010#.VjiZ5rKqqko|title=Details 2010|publisher=Box Office India|accessdate=3 November 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151101184042/http://boxofficeindia.com/Years/years_detail/2010#.VjiZ5rKqqko|archivedate=1 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He teamed up with [[Ekta Kapoor]]'s [[Balaji Motion Pictures]] to produce the supernatural thriller ''[[Ek Thi Daayan]]'' (2013). Dealing with the themes of [[witchcraft]], the film was based on 'Mobius Trips', a short story written by [[Konkona Sen Sharma]]'s father.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibnlive.com/news/india/read-the-story-that-inspired-ek-thi-daayan-605057.html|title=Read the story that inspired 'Ek Thi Daayan'|publisher=CNN-IBN|date=24 April 2013|accessdate=13 December 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160126052851/http://www.ibnlive.com/news/india/read-the-story-that-inspired-ek-thi-daayan-605057.html|archivedate=26 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It received mixed reviews from critics,<ref>{{cite news|title=Critics' review: Ek Thi Daayan is a blend of horror, psycho thriller|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/movie-reviews/critics-review-ek-thi-daayan-is-a-blend-of-horror-psycho-thriller/story-sdVsqM9dgZoC5QZK3JqmXK.html|work=[[Hindustan Times]]|date=19 April 2013|accessdate=29 April 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222155546/http://www.hindustantimes.com/movie-reviews/critics-review-ek-thi-daayan-is-a-blend-of-horror-psycho-thriller/story-sdVsqM9dgZoC5QZK3JqmXK.html|archivedate=22 December 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> but proved to be a profitable venture at the box-office.<ref>{{cite web|title=Box-Office Verdicts Of Major Bollywood Releases Of 2013|url=http://www.koimoi.com/box-office-bollywood-films-of-2013/|publisher=Koimoi|date=22 April 2013|accessdate=30 July 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140803012622/http://www.koimoi.com/box-office-bollywood-films-of-2013/|archivedate=3 August 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nHis next production venture was ''[[Dedh Ishqiya]]'', a sequel to the 2010 film ''Ishqiya''. Starring [[Madhuri Dixit]], Naseeruddin Shah, [[Huma Qureshi (actress)|Huma Qureshi]] and Arshad Warsi; the film was a critical and commercial success with earning \u20b9270 million (US$4.1 million) in India and abroad.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/dedh-ishqiya-review-roundup-better-than-prequel-must-watch-for-madhuri-533774|title='Dedh Ishqiya' Review Roundup: Better than Prequel; Must Watch for Madhuri|last=Mehta|first=Ankita|publisher=[[International Business Times]]|date=10 January 2014|accessdate=3 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602131424/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/dedh-ishqiya-review-roundup-better-than-prequel-must-watch-for-madhuri-533774|archivedate=2 June 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/indiarealtime/2014/01/10/full-marks-to-dedh-ishqiya/|title=Full Marks to 'Dedh Ishqiya'|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=10 January 2014|accessdate=23 February 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140214044854/https://blogs.wsj.com/indiarealtime/2014/01/10/full-marks-to-dedh-ishqiya/|archivedate=14 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2015, Bhardwaj wrote and co-produced [[Meghna Gulzar]]'s crime drama ''[[Talvar (film)|Talvar]]''. The film was based on the [[2008 Noida double murder case]], and starred Irrfan Khan, Konkana Sen Sharma and [[Neeraj Kabi]].<ref name=\"talvar\">{{cite news|url=http://www.firstpost.com/fwire/bollywood-fwire/talvar-review-vishal-bharadwajs-retelling-of-the-aarushi-hemraj-murders-will-leave-you-shaken-and-heartbroken-2452594.html|title=Talvar review: Vishal Bharadwaj's retelling of Aarushi-Hemraj murders will leave you heartbroken|last=Pal|first=Deepanjana|publisher=[[Firstpost]]|date=4 October 2015|accessdate=3 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151018180041/http://www.firstpost.com/fwire/bollywood-fwire/talvar-review-vishal-bharadwajs-retelling-of-the-aarushi-hemraj-murders-will-leave-you-shaken-and-heartbroken-2452594.html|archivedate=18 October 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''Talvar'' premiered at the [[2015 Toronto International Film Festival]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/meghna-gulzar-s-talvar-to-be-screened-at-toronto-film-fest/story-sd5ENiWqHFqPrAxxf58ijL.html|title=Meghna Gulzar's Talvar to be screened at Toronto Film Fest|last=Bhaskaran|first=Gautaman|work=Hindustan Times|date=3 August 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151104001809/http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/meghna-gulzar-s-talvar-to-be-screened-at-toronto-film-fest/story-sd5ENiWqHFqPrAxxf58ijL.html|archivedate=4 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and was released in India on 2 October 2015, to positive reviews from critics.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-top-5-talvar-reviews-what-do-critics-think-of-meghna-gulzar-s-film-2131006|title=Top 5 'Talvar' reviews: What do critics think of Meghna Gulzar's film?|work=[[Daily News and Analysis]]|date=2 October 2015|accessdate=3 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151109143226/http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-top-5-talvar-reviews-what-do-critics-think-of-meghna-gulzar-s-film-2131006|archivedate=9 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Playback singer===\nApart from composing music, Bhardwaj has also lent his voice for various songs for films like ''Omkara'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2006/jul/12omkara.htm|title=Omkara's music rocks|last=Verma|first=Sukanya|publisher=Rediff.com|date=12 July 2006|accessdate=7 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304124902/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2006/jul/12omkara.htm|archivedate=4 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''[[No Smoking (2007 film)|No Smoking]]'' (2007),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.last.fm/music/Sukhwinder+Singh,+Daler+Mehndi+&+Vishal+Bhardwaj/_/Kash+Laga|title=Kash Laga|publisher=[[Last.fm]]|accessdate=7 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160309123455/http://www.last.fm/music/Sukhwinder+Singh%2C+Daler+Mehndi+%26+Vishal+Bhardwaj/_/Kash+Laga|archivedate=9 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''[[U Me Aur Hum]]'' (2008),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/moviemicro/musiccriticreview/id/201801|title=U Me Aur Hm (2008)|last=Tuteja|first=Joginder|publisher=Bollywood Hungama|date=16 February 2008|accessdate=7 November 2015}}</ref> ''Kaminey'',<ref>{{cite web|title='Kaminey' music experimental, power-packed|url=http://archive.mid-day.com/entertainment/2009/jul/090709-kaminey-music-review.htm|work=Mid Day|date=9 July 2009|accessdate=30 May 2013}}</ref> ''[[Striker (2010 film)|Striker]]'' (2010),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://saregama.wordpress.com/2010/01/21/music-review-striker/|title=Music Review: Striker|publisher=[[Saregama]]|date=21 January 2010|accessdate=7 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304134542/https://saregama.wordpress.com/2010/01/21/music-review-striker/|archivedate=4 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''7 Khoon Maaf'',<ref>{{cite news|title=Music Review: 7 Khoon Maaf|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/music/music-review-7-khoon-maaf/story-8ZPEUdcmSDYyhlZyFfViqL.html|last=Hemrajani|first=Nikhil|work=Hindustan Times|date=10 February 2011|accessdate=22 April 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304111756/http://www.hindustantimes.com/music/music-review-7-khoon-maaf/story-8ZPEUdcmSDYyhlZyFfViqL.html|archivedate=4 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''Matru Ki Bijlee Ka Mandola'' and ''Haider''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibnlive.com/news/buzz/matru-ki-bijlee-music-review-it-has-a-new-flavour-528819.html|title='Matru Ki Bijlee' Music Review: It has a new flavour|publisher=CNN-IBN|date=28 December 2012|accessdate=7 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304070933/http://www.ibnlive.com/news/buzz/matru-ki-bijlee-music-review-it-has-a-new-flavour-528819.html|archivedate=4 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gaana.com/album/haider-|title=Haider|publisher=[[Gaana.com]]|accessdate=7 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151110002317/http://gaana.com/album/haider-/|archivedate=10 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Craft and style==\nBhardwaj's films are often twisted with portrayal of character's with grey shades.<ref name=\"shakespeare\">{{cite news|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/haider-maqbool-omkara-vishal-bhardwaj-and-his-obsession-with-the-anti-hero-674272|title=Haider, Maqbool, Omkara: Vishal Bhardwaj's League of Extraordinary Anti-Heroes|last=Bedi|first=Shibani|publisher=NDTV|date=3 October 2014|accessdate=3 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160603090340/http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/haider-maqbool-omkara-vishal-bhardwaj-and-his-obsession-with-the-anti-hero-674272|archivedate=3 June 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He also frequently adapts short stories and plays in films. ''The Blue Umbrella'' and ''7 Khoon Maaf'' were adapted from [[Ruskin Bond]]'s short stories.<ref name=bond>{{cite news|title=Ruskin Bond on 7 Khoon Maaf|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1110217/jsp/entertainment/story_13592167.jsp|author=Chakraborty Lahiri, Samhita|work=[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph]]|date=17 February 2011|accessdate=22 April 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110831142022/http://www.telegraphindia.com/1110217/jsp/entertainment/story_13592167.jsp|archivedate=31 August 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''Maqbool'', ''Omkara'' and ''Haider'' were adaptations of William Shakespeare's tragedies.<ref name=\"shakespeare\"/> Some of Bhardwaj's films takes clues from real-life incidents. The [[Kashmir conflict]] was shown in ''Haider'',<ref name=\"peer\"/> the [[Organised crime in India|Mumbai underworld]] in ''Maqbool'',<ref name=\"shakespeare\"/> and ''Talvar'' being based on the [[2008 Noida double murder case]].<ref name=\"talvar\"/> Bhardwaj frequently collaborates with writer-lyricist Gulzar and calls him his \"father\" and \"mentor\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/music/gulzar-i-have-lived-longer-because-of-vishal-bhardwaj-635169|title=Gulzar: I have lived longer because of Vishal Bhardwaj|publisher=NDTV|date=13 September 2013|accessdate=3 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160603090342/http://movies.ndtv.com/music/gulzar-i-have-lived-longer-because-of-vishal-bhardwaj-635169|archivedate=3 June 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Most of the treatments of his films are like documentaries. ''Haider'' was co-written by journalist-writer Basharat Peer, who was an eyewitness of the Kashmir conflict.<ref name=\"peer\"/> He evolves his script until the filming.\n\nBhardwaj is influenced by the film-making styles of [[Satyajit Ray]], [[Ritwik Ghatak]], Akira Kurosawa and Krzysztof Kie\u015blowski.<ref name=\"filmmaking\">{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1150214/jsp/t2/story_3182.jsp#.VyhmpoR97IU|title=Why Vishal Bhardwaj hates award functions, why he loves ray, why he won't make a Chennai Express...|last=Roy|first=Priyanka|work=The Telegraph|date=14 February 2015|accessdate=3 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602132539/http://www.telegraphindia.com/1150214/jsp/t2/story_3182.jsp#.VyhmpoR97IU|archivedate=2 June 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Kieslowski's ''[[Dekalog]]'' (1989) inspired him to become a film-maker.<ref name=\"filmmaking\"/> Veteran actor [[Naseeruddin Shah]] says: \"I think he makes interesting films, even though I haven\u2019t liked all his works. But even his poor work is more interesting than a lot of people\u2019s so-called good work.\u201d<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-i-wasn-t-dying-to-do-vishal-bhardwaj-s-film-naseeruddin-shah-1509458|title=wasn't dying to do Vishal Bhardwaj's film: Naseeruddin Shah|last=Mazumder|first=Jayeeta|work=Daily News and Analysis|date=18 February 2011|accessdate=3 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816110005/http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-i-wasn-t-dying-to-do-vishal-bhardwaj-s-film-naseeruddin-shah-1509458|archivedate=16 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\nIn 1997, Bhardwaj won the [[Filmfare RD Burman Award for New Music Talent]] for ''Maachis''.<ref name=\"makdee\"/> He later won the [[National Film Award for Best Music Direction]] for ''Godmother''.<ref name=\"god\"/> He then went on to win two consecutive awards: ''The Blue Umbrella'', which won the [[National Film Award for Best Children's Film]],<ref name=\"umbrella\"/> and [[National Film Award \u2013 Special Jury Award (Feature Film)|National Film Award \u2013 Special Jury Award]] for ''Omkara''.<ref name=\"omkara\"/> Bhardwaj got two [[Filmfare Awards|Filmfare]] nominations for ''Kaminey'' in [[Filmfare Award for Best Director|Best Director]] and [[Filmfare Award for Best Music Director|Best Music Director]] categories.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|title=Filmfare 2009 nominations|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Filmfare-2009-nominations/articleshow/5575557.cms|work=The Times of India|date=15 February 2010|accessdate=8 May 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160225035625/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Filmfare-2009-nominations/articleshow/5575557.cms|archivedate=25 February 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nHe won his second National Film Award for Best Music Direction, for his production venture ''Ishqiya''.<ref name=\"nfa\"/> At the [[62nd National Film Awards]], Bhardwaj won his third [[National Film Award for Best Music Direction|Best Music Direction]] and [[National Film Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay]] award for ''Haider''.<ref name=\"dialogue\"/> In 2016, Bhardwaj was awarded with [[Yash Bharti Award]] by the [[Government of Uttar Pradesh]] for his contribution in the field of cinema.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/lucknow/Eminent-achievers-to-get-Yash-Bharti-Award-today/articleshow/51486494.cms|title=Eminent achievers to get Yash Bharti Award today|work=The Times of India|date=21 March 2016|accessdate=24 March 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160331012702/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/lucknow/Eminent-achievers-to-get-Yash-Bharti-Award-today/articleshow/51486494.cms|archivedate=31 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He also received his second National Film Award for Best Screenplay for writing ''Talvar''.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite press_release|title=63rd National Film Awards|url=http://dff.nic.in/writereaddata/Winners_of_63rd_NFA_2015.pdf|publisher=Directorate of Film Festivals|date=28 March 2016|accessdate=28 March 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161007194418/http://dff.nic.in/writereaddata/Winners_of_63rd_NFA_2015.pdf|archivedate=7 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Bhardwaj's Shakespearean trilogy\u2014 ''Maqbool'', ''Omkara'' and ''Haider''\u2014 was screened as part of an event marking William Shakespear's 400th death anniversary co-hosted by the [[British Film Institute]] in London.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mumbaimirror.com/entertainment/bollywood/Vishals-not-done-with-the-Bard-yet/articleshow/52082213.cms|title=Vishal's Not Done With The Bard Yet|last=Bhattacharya|first=Roshmila|work=[[Mumbai Mirror]]|date=3 May 2016|accessdate=3 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503124039/http://mumbaimirror.com/entertainment/bollywood/Vishals-not-done-with-the-Bard-yet/articleshow/52082213.cms|archivedate=3 May 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2019, Bhardwaj won the [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Music Director]] for his second [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]] film ''[[Carbon (2018 film)|Carbon]]'' (2018).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/malayalam/movies/news/nimisha-sajayan-jayasurya-and-soubin-shahir-win-big-at-the-kerala-state-film-awards-2019/articleshow/68179596.cms|title=Nimisha Sajayan, Jayasurya and Soubin Shahir win big at the Kerala State Film Awards 2019|last=Soman|first=Deepa|work=The Times of India|date=27 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Key\n| style=\"background:#ffc;\"| {{dagger|alt=Films that have not yet been released}}\n| Denotes films that have not yet been released\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |Title\n! scope=\"col\" |Year\n! Director\n! Producer\n! Screenwriter\n! Music Composer\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Abhay (The Fearless)]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1995\n| \n|\n| \n| {{ya}}\n| \n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Fauji (1995 film)|Fauji]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1995\n|\n|\n| \n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Sanshodhan]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1996\n|\n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Maachis]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1996\n|\n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n| [[Filmfare RD Burman Award for New Music Talent]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Tunnu Ki Tina]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1997\n|\n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Betaabi]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1997\n|\n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Sham Ghansham''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1998\n|\n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Satya (1998 film)|Satya]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1998\n|\n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Chachi 420]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1998\n|\n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Daya (film)|Daya]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1998\n|\n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n| [[Malayalam cinema|Malayalam film]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Jahan Tum Le Chalo]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1999\n|\n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Hu Tu Tu]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1999\n|\n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Godmother (film)|Godmother]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1999\n|\n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n| [[National Film Award for Best Music Direction]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Dil Pe Mat Le Yaar]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2000\n|\n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Choo Lenge Akash''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2000\n|\n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Love Ke Liye Kuch Bhi Karega]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2001\n|\n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Mulaqaat]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2002\n|\n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Makdee]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2002\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Kagaar: Life on the Edge]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2003\n|\n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Danav''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2003\n|\n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Chupke Se]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2003\n|\n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Maqbool]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2003\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Paanch]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2003\n|\n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n| Unreleased\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Bhagmati (2005 film)|Bhagmati]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2005\n|\n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Ramji Londonwale]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2005\n|\n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[The Blue Umbrella (2005 film)|The Blue Umbrella]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2005\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| [[National Film Award for Best Children's Film]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Omkara (2006 film)|Omkara]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2006\n| {{ya}}\n| \n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| [[National Film Award \u2013 Special Jury Award (Feature Film)|National Film Award \u2013 Special Jury Award]]<br/>Nomination\u2014[[Filmfare Award for Best Director]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Nishabd]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2007\n|\n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Blood Brothers (2007 Indian film)|Blood Brothers]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2007\n| {{ya}}\n|\n| {{ya}}\n| \n| Short film\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[No Smoking (2007 film)|No Smoking]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2007\n| \n| {{ya}}\n| \n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Dus Kahaniyaan]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2007\n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[U Me Aur Hum]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2008\n|\n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Haal-e-Dil]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2008\n|\n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Kaminey]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2009\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n|  Nominated\u2014Filmfare Award for Best Director<br/>Nominated\u2014[[Filmfare Award for Best Music Director]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Ishqiya]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2010\n|\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n|  National Film Award for Best Music Direction<br/>Nominated\u2014Filmfare Award for Best Director\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[7 Khoon Maaf]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2011\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Matru Ki Bijlee Ka Mandola]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2013\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Ek Thi Daayan]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2013\n|\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Dedh Ishqiya]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2014\n|\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Haider (film)|Haider]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2014\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| [[National Film Award for Best Screenplay]]<br/>National Film Award for Best Music Direction<br/>Nominated\u2014Filmfare Award for Best Director\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Drishyam (2015 film)|Drishyam]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2015\n|\n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Talvar (film)|Talvar]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2015\n|\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| [[National Film Award for Best Screenplay]]<br/>Nominated\u2014Filmfare Award for Best Film\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Hawaizaada]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2015\n|\n| \n| \n| {{ya}}\n| \n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Madaari]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2016\n|\n| \n| \n| {{ya}}\n| \n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Motu Patlu: King Of Kings]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2016\n|\n| \n| \n| {{ya}}\n| Animation film\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Rangoon (2017 Hindi film)|Rangoon]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2017\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| \n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|''[[Carbon (2018 film)|Carbon]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2018\n| \n| \n| \n| {{ya}}\n| Malayalam film<br/>[[Kerala State Film Award for Best Music Director]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|''[[Pataakha]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2018\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| \n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|''[[Sonchiriya]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2019\n| \n| \n| \n| {{ya}}\n| \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons ca