e for Capitalism |  publisher= [[Haymarket Books]] | year = 2012 | isbn = 978-1-60846-247-6}}\n* {{cite book | last = Wood | first = Ellen Meiksins | authorlink = Ellen Meiksins Wood | title = The Origin of Capitalism: A Longer View |  publisher= [[Verso]] | year = 2002 | isbn = 978-1-85984-392-5}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Capitalism}}\n{{EB1922 Poster}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Wiktionary}}\n* {{In Our Time|Capitalism|p00545kv|Capitalism}}\n* [https://www.britannica.com/topic/capitalism Capitalism] at ''[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]'' Online. \n* [http://www.hup.harvard.edu/features/capitalism-and-its-discontents.html Selected Titles on Capitalism and Its Discontents]. [[Harvard University Press]].\n\n{{library resources box|by=no|onlinebooks=no|others=no|about=yes|label=Capitalism}}\n{{aspects of capitalism}}\n{{Marxist & Communist phraseology}}\n{{Western culture}}\n{{Portal bar|Companies|Capitalism|Politics}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Capitalism| ]]\n[[Category:Economic ideologies]]\n[[Category:Economic liberalism]]\n[[Category:Production economics]]\n[[Category:Profit]]\n[[Category:Social philosophy]]\n[[Category:Western culture]]\n", "name_user": "InedibleHulk", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTypes of capitalism:Implied.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capitalism"}
{"title_page": "Michelle Stilwell", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name         = Michelle Stilwell\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of the Legislative Assembly|MLA]]\n| image        = Michelle Stilwell 2015b.jpg\n| caption      = Stilwell at the 2015 Parapan American Games\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1974|07|04}}\n| birth_place  = [[Winnipeg, Manitoba]], Canada\n| residence    = [[Parksville, British Columbia|Parksville]], [[British Columbia]]<ref name=bio/>\n| assembly1    = British Columbia Legislative\n| constituency_AM1 = [[Parksville-Qualicum]]\n| term_start1  = May 14, 2013\n| term_end1    = \n| predecessor1 = [[Ron Cantelon]]\n| successor1   = \n| office2      = Minister of Social Development and Social Innovation of [[Executive Council of British Columbia|British Columbia]]\n| premier2     = [[Christy Clark]]\n| term_start2  = February 2, 2015\n| term_end2    = July 18, 2017\n| predecessor2 = [[Don McRae (politician)|Don McRae]]\n| successor2   = [[Shane Simpson]]\n| office3      = Parliamentary Secretary for Healthy Living and Seniors\n| premier3     = [[Christy Clark]]\n| term_start3  = June 2013\n| term_end3    = February 2, 2015\n| predecessor3 = \n| successor3   = Incumbent\n| party        = [[British Columbia Liberal Party|Liberal]]\n| religion     =\n| profession   = \n| spouse       = {{married|Mark Stilwell|1997}}\n| children     = \n| module       = {{Infobox sportsperson|child=yes\n| height           = 170 cm<ref name=bio/>\n| weight           = 51 kg\n| disability_class = [[T52 (classification)|T52]]\n| medaltemplates   = \n{{MedalCountry|{{CAN}}}}\n{{MedalSport | Women's [[wheelchair basketball]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Paralympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2000 Summer Paralympics|2000 Sydney]] | [[Wheelchair basketball at the 2000 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women|Team]]}}\n{{MedalSport | Women's [[para athletics]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Paralympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2008 Summer Paralympics|2008 Beijing]] | [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's 100 metres T52|100m T52]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2008 Summer Paralympics|2008 Beijing]] | [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's 200 metres T52|200m T52]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2012 Summer Paralympics|2012 London]] | [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's 200 metres T52|200m T52]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2012 Summer Paralympics|2012 London]] | [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's 100 metres T52|100m T52]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio de Janeiro]] | [[Athletics at the 2016 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's 100 metres|100m T52]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio de Janeiro]] | [[Athletics at the 2016 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's 400 metres|400m T52]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Parapan American Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2015 Parapan American Games|2015 Toronto]]|[[Athletics at the 2015 Parapan American Games \u2013 Women's 100 metres T52|100m T52]]}}\n}}}}\n\n'''Michelle Stilwell''' (''nee'' Bauknecht; born July 4, 1974) is a Canadian wheelchair racer and politician. She is the only female Paralympic athlete to win gold medals in two separate summer sport events. Stilwell was elected to the [[Legislative Assembly of British Columbia]] as a [[British Columbia Liberal Party|BC Liberal]] candidate for [[Parksville-Qualicum]] in the [[2013 British Columbia general election|2013 provincial election]]. She represented Canada at the [[2000 Summer Paralympics]], [[2008 Summer Paralympics]], and [[2012 Summer Paralympics]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nStilwell was born on July 4, 1974, in [[Winnipeg, Manitoba]], Canada.<ref name = \"bio\">{{cite web |title=Michelle Stilwell |url=https://paralympic.ca/team-canada/michelle-stilwell |website=paralympic.ca |accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref> While attending [[River East Collegiate]], she broke her neck from a fall and became an incomplete quadriplegic.<ref>{{cite web |title=Meet the 5 Paralympic athletes with ties to Manitoba |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/manitoba-paralympians-get-ready-for-rio-games-1.3742331 |website=cbc.ca |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |date=September 5, 2016}}</ref> After the accident, she competed in [[wheelchair basketball]], through which she met her husband Mark at the 1996 National Championships in Montreal.<ref name = \"Prest\">{{cite news|title=A Gift More Precious Than Gold|last=Prest|first=Ashley|date=September 30, 2008|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Manitoba|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-sep-30-2008-1602860/}}{{free access}}</ref> Stilwell eventually moved to [[Calgary]] where she completed her [[Bachelor of Science]] degree at the [[University of Calgary]] in 1999.<ref name = \"bio\"/>\n\n==Paralympic career==\n[[File:Michelle Stilwell - 2013 IPC Athletics World Championships.jpg|thumb|left|Stilwell at the 2013 IPC Athletics World Championships]]\nStilwell stayed in Calgary from 1997 until 2000 to train for the [[Canada women's national wheelchair basketball team]].<ref name = \"Prest\"/> She competed as a reserve for Team Canada at the [[2000 Paralympic Games]], where her team won a gold medal.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lonely at the Top |url=http://www.canada.com/story.html?id=b0bf13ea-d410-4975-b477-febf1df5ec94 |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |publisher=Vancouver Sun |date=May 31, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151017080306/http://www.canada.com/story.html?id=b0bf13ea-d410-4975-b477-febf1df5ec94 |archivedate=December 30, 2018}}</ref> Afterwards, Stilwell, her husband Mark, and their newborn son moved to Vancouver Island.<ref name = \"x\">{{cite news |title=Canadian Paralympian Michelle Stilwell's toughest competition is herself |url=https://nationalpost.com/sports/canadian-paralympian-michelle-stilwells-biggest-challenge-is-herself |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |publisher=National Post |date=August 28, 2012}}</ref>\n\nHowever, Stilwell was forced to forgo wheelchair basketball after undergoing surgery for a herniated brain stem.<ref>{{cite web |title=Winnipeg-born athlete continues to overcome adversity |url=http://www.themanitoban.com/2012/02/winnipeg-born-athlete-continues-to-overcome-adversity/8762/ |website=themanitoban.com |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |date=March 3, 2020}}</ref> Although was unable to compete at a national level, Stilwell continued to play basketball locally where she was spotted by Coach Peter Lawless, who convinced her to try for wheelchair racing.<ref name = \"x\"/> Stilwell qualified for the [[2008 Paralympic Games]] where she won two gold medals in the woman's [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's 200 metres T52|T52 200m]] and [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's 100 metres T52|100m]] events.<ref>{{cite web |title=Canadian track star Stilwell takes 2nd Paralympic gold |url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/olympics-summer/canadian-track-star-stilwell-takes-2nd-paralympic-gold-1.716905 |website=cbc.ca |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |date=September 15, 2008}}</ref> This was followed by three gold medals (with World Championship records) and one silver at the 2011 World Championships in [[Christchurch]], [[New Zealand]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Clarke |first1=James |title=Mikey returns with a handful of gold, silver |url=https://www.pqbnews.com/sports/mikey-returns-with-a-handful-of-gold-silver/ |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |publisher=Parksville Qualicum Beach News |date=February 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[London 2012 Paralympic Games]], Stilwell defended her Paralympic gold medal in the women's [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's 200 metres T52|200m]] in 33.80 seconds, shattering her Games record by over two seconds.<ref>{{cite news |title=Canada's Michelle Stilwell defends Paralympic title in T52 200-metre final |url=https://nationalpost.com/sports/canadas-michelle-stilwell-defends-paralympic-title-in-t52-200-metre-final |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |publisher=National Post |date=September 1, 2012}}</ref> Four days later, Stilwell captured a silver medal in the [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's 100 metres T52|100m]] after mishap caused her to fall behind [[Marieke Vervoort]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kingston |first1=Gary |title=Canada\u2019s Michelle Stilwell sees silver lining in Paralympic wheelchair race result |url=http://www.vancouversun.com/Canada+Michelle+Stilwell+sees+silver+lining+Paralympic+wheelchair+race+result/7195888/story.html |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |publisher=Vancouver Sun |date=September 5, 2012}}</ref> The following year, she competed in the [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships]] and set a new world record in the women's T52 class 800 metres.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kingston |first1=Gary |title=MLA Michelle Stilwell sets world wheelchair record |url=http://www.vancouversun.com/sports/Michelle+Stilwell+sets+world+wheelchair+record/8709320/story.html |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |publisher=Vancouver Sun |date=July 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, her last Paralympic Games, Stilwell earned a gold medal while also setting a Paralympics record during the T52 wheelchair 400 metres race, with a time of one minute and 5.42 seconds.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dheensaw |first1=Cleve |title=Michelle Stilwell wins 5th gold: 'It was the moment I was working for' |url=https://www.timescolonist.com/sports/michelle-stilwell-wins-5th-gold-it-was-the-moment-i-was-working-for-1.2340996 |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |publisher=Times Colonist |date=September 10, 2016}}</ref> The following year, Stilwell announced her retirement from competitive sports<ref>{{cite web |title=Michelle Stilwell announces retirement |url=https://athletics.ca/michelle-stilwell-announces-retirement/ |website=athletics.ca |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |date=February 8, 2017}}</ref> and was inducted into the [[BC Sports Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Former Wheelchair Basketball Athlete Michelle Stilwell and Coach Tim Frick To Be Inducted into B.C. Sports Hall of Fame |url=https://www.wheelchairbasketball.ca/news_press/former-wheelchair-basketball-athlete-michelle-stilwell-coach-tim-frick-inducted-b-c-sports-hall-fame/ |website=wheelchairbasketball.ca |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |date=December 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nIn 2013, Stilwell campaigned to become the [[British Columbia Liberal Party|BC Liberal]] candidate for [[Parksville-Qualicum]] in the [[2013 British Columbia general election|2013 provincial election]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mason |first1=Gary |title=Paralympic champ turned B.C. politician faces her toughest race yet |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/british-columbia/paralympic-champ-turned-bc-politician-faces-her-toughest-race-yet/article11492194/ |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |publisher=Globe and Mail |date=April 23, 2013}}</ref> She was eventually elected to the [[Legislative Assembly of British Columbia]] served as [[Caucus Chair]] and [[Parliamentary Secretary]]  for [[Healthy Living and Seniors]] for two years before being sworn in as [[Minister for Social Development and Social Innovation]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shaw |first1=Rob |title=Rookie MLA tapped for cabinet as social development minister resigns |url=http://www.vancouversun.com/health/Rookie+tapped+cabinet+social+development+minister+resigns/10773227/story.html |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |publisher=Vancouver Sun |date=January 30, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral record==\n{{British Columbia provincial election, 2017/Parksville-Qualicum}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Michelle Stilwell}}\n* {{IPC athlete|id=michelle-stilwell|old_id=687342}}\n* {{CPC profile|michelle-stilwell}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170410214552/https://www.coeurhandisport.fr/athletes_etrangers/ACDH-ETR-a49f88.php Michelle Stilwell - C\u0153ur Handisport]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140913141925/http://www.bcliberals.com/team/mla/michelle-stilwell/ Official Liberal Party Website]\n* [http://www.mikeystilwell.com/ Official Wheelchair Racing Website]\n\n{{British Columbia MLAs}}\n{{Christy Clark Ministry}}\n{{Canadian medallists at the 2012 Summer Paralympics}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stilwell, Michelle}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Wheelchair basketball players at the 2000 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:British Columbia Liberal Party MLAs]]\n[[Category:Canadian politicians with physical disabilities]]\n[[Category:Canadian sportsperson-politicians]]\n[[Category:Canadian female wheelchair racers]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of Canada]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2000 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Members of the Executive Council of British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Olympic wheelchair racers of Canada]]\n[[Category:Paralympic gold medalists for Canada]]\n[[Category:Paralympic wheelchair racers]]\n[[Category:People from Parksville, British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Winnipeg]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Winnipeg]]\n[[Category:Women MLAs in British Columbia]]\n[[Category:World record holders in Paralympic athletics]]\n[[Category:Paralympic silver medalists for Canada]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian women politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name         = Michelle Stilwell\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of the Legislative Assembly|MLA]]\n| image        = Michelle Stilwell 2015b.jpg\n| caption      = Stilwell at the 2015 Parapan American Games\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1974|07|04}}\n| birth_place  = [[Winnipeg, Manitoba]], Canada\n| residence    = [[Parksville, British Columbia|Parksville]], [[British Columbia]]<ref name=bio/>\n| assembly1    = British Columbia Legislative\n| constituency_AM1 = [[Parksville-Qualicum]]\n| term_start1  = May 14, 2013\n| term_end1    = \n| predecessor1 = [[Ron Cantelon]]\n| successor1   = \n| office2      = Minister of Social Development and Social Innovation of [[Executive Council of British Columbia|British Columbia]]\n| premier2     = [[Christy Clark]]\n| term_start2  = February 2, 2015\n| term_end2    = July 18, 2017\n| predecessor2 = [[Don McRae (politician)|Don McRae]]\n| successor2   = [[Shane Simpson]]\n| office3      = Parliamentary Secretary for Healthy Living and Seniors\n| premier3     = [[Christy Clark]]\n| term_start3  = June 2013\n| term_end3    = February 2, 2015\n| predecessor3 = \n| successor3   = Incumbent\n| party        = [[British Columbia Liberal Party|Liberal]]\n| religion     =\n| profession   = \n| spouse       = {{married|Mark Stilwell|1997}}\n| children     = \n| module       = {{Infobox sportsperson|child=yes\n| height           = 170 cm<ref name=bio/>\n| weight           = 51 kg\n| disability_class = [[T52 (classification)|T52]]\n| medaltemplates   = \n{{MedalCountry|{{CAN}}}}\n{{MedalSport | Women's [[wheelchair basketball]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Paralympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2000 Summer Paralympics|2000 Sydney]] | [[Wheelchair basketball at the 2000 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women|Team]]}}\n{{MedalSport | Women's [[para athletics]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Paralympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2008 Summer Paralympics|2008 Beijing]] | [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's 100 metres T52|100m T52]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2008 Summer Paralympics|2008 Beijing]] | [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's 200 metres T52|200m T52]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2012 Summer Paralympics|2012 London]] | [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's 200 metres T52|200m T52]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2012 Summer Paralympics|2012 London]] | [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's 100 metres T52|100m T52]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio de Janeiro]] | [[Athletics at the 2016 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's 100 metres|100m T52]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio de Janeiro]] | [[Athletics at the 2016 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's 400 metres|400m T52]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Parapan American Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2015 Parapan American Games|2015 Toronto]]|[[Athletics at the 2015 Parapan American Games \u2013 Women's 100 metres T52|100m T52]]}}\n}}}}\n\n'''Michelle Stilwell''' (''nee'' Bauknecht; born July 4, 1974) is a Canadian wheelchair racer and politician. She is the only female Paralympic athlete to win gold medals in two separate summer sport events. Stilwell was elected to the [[Legislative Assembly of British Columbia]] as a [[British Columbia Liberal Party|BC Liberal]] candidate for [[Parksville-Qualicum]] in the [[2013 British Columbia general election|2013 provincial election]]. She represented Canada at the [[2000 Summer Paralympics]], [[2008 Summer Paralympics]], and [[2012 Summer Paralympics]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nStilwell was born on July 4, 1974, in [[Winnipeg, Manitoba]], Canada.<ref name = \"bio\">{{cite web |title=Michelle Stilwell |url=https://paralympic.ca/team-canada/michelle-stilwell |website=paralympic.ca |accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref> While attending [[River East Collegiate]], she broke her neck from a fall and became an incomplete quadriplegic.<ref>{{cite web |title=Meet the 5 Paralympic athletes with ties to Manitoba |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/manitoba-paralympians-get-ready-for-rio-games-1.3742331 |website=cbc.ca |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |date=September 5, 2016}}</ref> After the accident, she competed in [[wheelchair basketball]], through which she met her husband Mark at the 1996 National Championships in Montreal.<ref name = \"Prest\">{{cite news|title=A Gift More Precious Than Gold|last=Prest|first=Ashley|date=September 30, 2008|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Manitoba|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-sep-30-2008-1602860/}}{{free access}}</ref> Stilwell eventually moved to [[Calgary]] where she completed her [[Bachelor of Science]] degree at the [[University of Calgary]] in 1999.<ref name = \"bio\"/> \n\n==Paralympic career==\n[[File:Michelle Stilwell - 2013 IPC Athletics World Championships.jpg|thumb|left|Stilwell at the 2013 IPC Athletics World Championships]]\nStilwell stayed in Calgary from 1997 until 2000 to train for the [[Canada women's national wheelchair basketball team]].<ref name = \"Prest\"/> She competed as a reserve for Team Canada at the [[2000 Paralympic Games]], where her team won a gold medal.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lonely at the Top |url=http://www.canada.com/story.html?id=b0bf13ea-d410-4975-b477-febf1df5ec94 |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |publisher=Vancouver Sun |date=May 31, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151017080306/http://www.canada.com/story.html?id=b0bf13ea-d410-4975-b477-febf1df5ec94 |archivedate=December 30, 2018}}</ref> Afterwards, Stilwell, her husband Mark, and their newborn son moved to Vancouver Island.<ref name = \"x\">{{cite news |title=Canadian Paralympian Michelle Stilwell's toughest competition is herself |url=https://nationalpost.com/sports/canadian-paralympian-michelle-stilwells-biggest-challenge-is-herself |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |publisher=National Post |date=August 28, 2012}}</ref>\n\nHowever, Stilwell was forced to forgo wheelchair basketball after undergoing surgery for a herniated brain stem.<ref>{{cite web |title=Winnipeg-born athlete continues to overcome adversity |url=http://www.themanitoban.com/2012/02/winnipeg-born-athlete-continues-to-overcome-adversity/8762/ |website=themanitoban.com |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |date=March 3, 2020}}</ref> Although was unable to compete at a national level, Stilwell continued to play basketball locally where she was spotted by Coach Peter Lawless, who convinced her to try for wheelchair racing.<ref name = \"x\"/> Stilwell qualified for the [[2008 Paralympic Games]] where she won two gold medals in the woman's [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's 200 metres T52|T52 200m]] and [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's 100 metres T52|100m]] events.<ref>{{cite web |title=Canadian track star Stilwell takes 2nd Paralympic gold |url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/olympics-summer/canadian-track-star-stilwell-takes-2nd-paralympic-gold-1.716905 |website=cbc.ca |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |date=September 15, 2008}}</ref> This was followed by three gold medals (with World Championship records) and one silver at the 2011 World Championships in [[Christchurch]], [[New Zealand]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Clarke |first1=James |title=Mikey returns with a handful of gold, silver |url=https://www.pqbnews.com/sports/mikey-returns-with-a-handful-of-gold-silver/ |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |publisher=Parksville Qualicum Beach News |date=February 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[London 2012 Paralympic Games]], Stilwell defended her Paralympic gold medal in the women\u2019s [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's 200 metres T52|200m]] in 33.80 seconds, shattering her Games record by over two seconds.<ref>{{cite news |title=Canada's Michelle Stilwell defends Paralympic title in T52 200-metre final |url=https://nationalpost.com/sports/canadas-michelle-stilwell-defends-paralympic-title-in-t52-200-metre-final |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |publisher=National Post |date=September 1, 2012}}</ref> Four days later, Stilwell captured a silver medal in the [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's 100 metres T52|100m]] after mishap caused her to fall behind [[Marieke Vervoort]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kingston |first1=Gary |title=Canada\u2019s Michelle Stilwell sees silver lining in Paralympic wheelchair race result |url=http://www.vancouversun.com/Canada+Michelle+Stilwell+sees+silver+lining+Paralympic+wheelchair+race+result/7195888/story.html |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |publisher=Vancouver Sun |date=September 5, 2012}}</ref> The following year, she competed in the [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships]] and set a new world record in the women\u2019s T52 class 800 metres.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kingston |first1=Gary |title=MLA Michelle Stilwell sets world wheelchair record |url=http://www.vancouversun.com/sports/Michelle+Stilwell+sets+world+wheelchair+record/8709320/story.html |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |publisher=Vancouver Sun |date=July 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, her last Paralympic Games, Stilwell earned a gold medal while also setting a Paralympics record during the T52 wheelchair 400 metres race, with a time of one minute and 5.42 seconds.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dheensaw |first1=Cleve |title=Michelle Stilwell wins 5th gold: 'It was the moment I was working for' |url=https://www.timescolonist.com/sports/michelle-stilwell-wins-5th-gold-it-was-the-moment-i-was-working-for-1.2340996 |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |publisher=Times Colonist |date=September 10, 2016}}</ref> The following year, Stilwell announced her retirement from competitive sports<ref>{{cite web |title=Michelle Stilwell announces retirement |url=https://athletics.ca/michelle-stilwell-announces-retirement/ |website=athletics.ca |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |date=February 8, 2017}}</ref> and was inducted into the [[BC Sports Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Former Wheelchair Basketball Athlete Michelle Stilwell and Coach Tim Frick To Be Inducted into B.C. Sports Hall of Fame |url=https://www.wheelchairbasketball.ca/news_press/former-wheelchair-basketball-athlete-michelle-stilwell-coach-tim-frick-inducted-b-c-sports-hall-fame/ |website=wheelchairbasketball.ca |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |date=December 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nIn 2013, Stilwell campaigned to become the [[British Columbia Liberal Party|BC Liberal]] candidate for [[Parksville-Qualicum]] in the [[2013 British Columbia general election|2013 provincial election]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mason |first1=Gary |title=Paralympic champ turned B.C. politician faces her toughest race yet |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/british-columbia/paralympic-champ-turned-bc-politician-faces-her-toughest-race-yet/article11492194/ |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |publisher=Globe and Mail |date=April 23, 2013}}</ref> She was eventually elected to the [[Legislative Assembly of British Columbia]] served as [[Caucus Chair]] and [[Parliamentary Secretary]]  for [[Healthy Living and Seniors]] for two years before being sworn in as [[Minister for Social Development and Social Innovation]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shaw |first1=Rob |title=Rookie MLA tapped for cabinet as social development minister resigns |url=http://www.vancouversun.com/health/Rookie+tapped+cabinet+social+development+minister+resigns/10773227/story.html |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |publisher=Vancouver Sun |date=January 30, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral record==\n{{British Columbia provincial election, 2017/Parksville-Qualicum}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Michelle Stilwell}}\n* {{IPC athlete|687342}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170410214552/https://www.coeurhandisport.fr/athletes_etrangers/ACDH-ETR-a49f88.php Michelle Stilwell - C\u0153ur Handisport]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140913141925/http://www.bcliberals.com/team/mla/michelle-stilwell/ Official Liberal Party Website]\n* [http://www.mikeystilwell.com/ Official Wheelchair Racing Website]\n\n{{British Columbia MLAs}}\n{{Christy Clark Ministry}}\n{{Canadian medallists at the 2012 Summer Paralympics}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stilwell, Michelle}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Wheelchair basketball players at the 2000 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:British Columbia Liberal Party MLAs]]\n[[Category:Canadian politicians with physical disabilities]]\n[[Category:Canadian sportsperson-politicians]]\n[[Category:Canadian female wheelchair racers]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of Canada]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2000 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Members of the Executive Council of British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Olympic wheelchair racers of Canada]]\n[[Category:Paralympic gold medalists for Canada]]\n[[Category:Paralympic wheelchair racers]]\n[[Category:People from Parksville, British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Winnipeg]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Winnipeg]]\n[[Category:Women MLAs in British Columbia]]\n[[Category:World record holders in Paralympic athletics]]\n[[Category:Paralympic silver medalists for Canada]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian women politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update IPC external link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michelle_Stilwell"}
